"1458–Male":"1458–Deceased","1458":"1458","1479":"1479","Abt 1410":"about 1410","1410":"1410","about 1450":"about 1450","Otterford, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Otterford, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Spalding, South Holland district, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Spalding, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Pitminster, Somerset West and Taunton district, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Pitminster, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Otterford, Somerset West and Taunton district, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Otterford, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Church of Saint Andrew and Saint Mary, Pitminster, Somerset West and Taunton district, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Pitminster, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Buller","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Bowler  . The surname is unlikely to have been derived from Middle English <i>buller(e)</i> ‘maker or publisher of bulls or papal edicts’. It is recorded only in the phrase <i>fals buller</i> ‘publisher of false bulls’. Old French <i>boleor</i>, <i>bouleur</i>, from which the word was borrowed, more generally meant ‘deceiver, trickster’, so possibly it also had this sense in Middle English but there is no evidence for it.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Bullard  .","German (also <b>Büller</b>): nickname for a man with a loud voice, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>büllen</i> ‘to roar, to bark’ (of imitative origin)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bullers","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire): variant of   Buller  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Bowler","meanings":["English (mainly East Midlands): occupational name from an unrecorded Middle English word <i>boler</i> ‘worker at a <i>bole</i> or lead-mining site’ (Middle English <i>bole</i> ‘bowl’), here denoting a round cavity on top of a high hill, where lead was smelted.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>bollere</i>, <i>boler</i>, <i>bolour</i>, <i>bulour</i> ‘maker or seller of bowls, dishes, or cups’ (from Old English <i>bolla</i> ‘bowl, drinking vessel’ + the agent suffix <i>-er</i>, and Old French <i>bole</i>, <i>bule</i> ‘bowl’). Medieval bowls were made of wood as well as of earthenware."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Buller was born about 1410, in Pitminster, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. She married Richard Treat about 1450. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1479, in Otterford, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 70, and was buried in Otterford, Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1410–1479":"umbes 1410–1479","1410–1479":"1410–1479","–Male":"Surnud","1458–Male":"1458–Surnud","1458":"1458","1479":"1479","Abt 1410":"umbes 1410","1410":"1410","about 1450":"umbes 1450","Otterford, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Otterford, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Spalding, South Holland district, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Spalding, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pitminster, Somerset West and Taunton district, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Pitminster, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Otterford, Somerset West and Taunton district, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Otterford, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Church of Saint Andrew and Saint Mary, Pitminster, Somerset West and Taunton district, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Pitminster, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1410–1479":"noin 1410–1479","1410–1479":"1410–1479","–Male":"Kuollut","1458–Male":"1458–Kuollut","1458":"1458","1479":"1479","Abt 1410":"noin 1410","1410":"1410","about 1450":"noin 1450","Otterford, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Otterford, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Spalding, South Holland district, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Spalding, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Pitminster, Somerset West and Taunton district, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Pitminster, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Otterford, Somerset West and Taunton district, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Otterford, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuninga